    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-03-19T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-03-19T10:00:00-05:00" n="639"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d639">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/9171: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morris</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-03-19T17:00:00+02:00"
                            >March 19, 1941—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 10:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1022. In official and diplomatic circles here there is general belief that
                    German-Greek relations are rapidly approaching a crisis which may result in
                    military action if German diplomatic pressure on Athens fails to achieve the
                    desired end in the near future. This opinion has been strengthened by reports in
                    the last few days of heavy troop movements to the southeast, the refusal of the
                    spokesman at the Foreign Office to comment on German-Greek relations which he
                    has heretofore consistently described as normal and the general feeling that
                    opening of German spring offensive will not be much longer delayed. It is also
                    stated in usually well-informed circles that Berlin desires to have the entire
                    Balkan situation well in hand before the Japanese-Soviet talks<note n="49"
                        xml:id="d639fn49">See <ref target="frus1941v04#pg_913">vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>, pp. 913</ref>–<ref
                            target="frus1941v04#pg_969">969</ref>, <hi rend="italic"
                        >passim</hi>.</note> in connection with Matsuoka’s<note n="50"
                        xml:id="d639fn50">Yosuke Matsuoka, Japanese Minister for Foreign
                        Affairs.</note> visit are opened.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Morris</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
